liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: A $1 million anonymous donation has been made to Zoos SA to fund its plans to home elephants at Monarto Safari Park. The chief executive of Zoos SA Elaine Benstead says the private donation brings the organisation much closer to its fundraising target of just over $2 million. It would cover the move of three Asian elephants from Perth and Auckland Zoos to Monarto. Ms Benstead says two other donors are contributing to a $150,000 fund-matching campaign.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Anonymous donor  gives $1m to Aussie zoo

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Police in Canada have laid further charges against a man suspected of selling a lethal chemical to dozens of people who died by suicide. Ontario police have added 12 charges of counselling or aiding suicide to two already faced by 57-year-old man Kenneth Law. They say he used various online sites to sell hundreds of parcels containing a lethal drug. UK police have said 88 people sent the chemical by the suspect subsequently died by suicide.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: More charges filed against man over lethal chemical

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Hurricane Idalia has strengthened over the Gulf of Mexico on its path towards Florida's Gulf Coast. It's forcing evacuations in low-lying coastal areas expected to be swamped when the storm makes landfall. A life-threatening storm surge of up to 3.5 metres above ground level is expected to hit some areas. The administrator of the US disaster relief agency FEMA Dianne Criswell says the storm will be deadly if people don't "get out of harms way".

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Good morning, Samuel Yang here to take you through another day on markets. Good to be back on the busines With ASX futures higher, it looks like it could be a positive start for the Australian share market. Overnight, all three major US stock indexes ended the session sharply higher, as investors looked ahead to crucial economic data due later this week that could sway the Federal Reserve's interest rate decisions in the coming months. US economic indicators released on Tuesday showed dampening consumer sentiment and job openings dropping to their lowest level since March 2021, offering evidence that the central bank's efforts to rein in inflation by throwing cold water on the economy are having their intended effect. "Today's data indicates that consumers are being cautious," said Peter Tuz, president of Chase Investment Counsel in Charlottesville, Virginia. "And a cautious consumer bodes well for efforts to control inflation; if consumers stop spending, prices will drop." ASX futures were up 47 points or 0.7 per cent to 7,209 at 7:18am AEST. At the same time, the Australian dollar was slightly down to 64.76 US cents.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: ASX eyes another gain
